WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.400
Welcome everybody, and thanks for attending today. We're going to talk about some tools that you could use to write larger Shiny apps

00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:12.560
that are easy to think about, or to reuse Shiny code across apps. And these tools are called modules.

00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:16.240
So let's start with the question, you know, what is a Shiny module?

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:23.280
And conceptually, it's pretty easy to answer. A Shiny module is a self-contained composable component of a Shiny app.

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:29.920
Self-contained means it's sort of like an R function. It does something, and it does it all by itself.

00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:36.240
It might take some input, it might return some output, but in the middle of the process, the app,

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:42.000
the module, doesn't need help from anything else to do its job. And because of this, Shiny modules

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.759
are composable. You could take multiple modules and put them together to make a Shiny app.

00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:52.080
And probably the easiest way to understand really what a Shiny app does, and what it looks like,

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:58.400
is to look at an actual Shiny app that uses modules. So let's go to RStudio.

00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:06.239
What I have here is a single file Shiny app. It makes this app over here, which is basically

00:01:06.239 --> 00:01:12.879
a recreation of Hans Rosling's Gapminder animations. So what I have is, you know,

00:01:13.519 --> 00:01:19.279
some different metrics about different countries on the planet, and particularly the life expectancy

00:01:19.279 --> 00:01:24.320
of those countries versus their GDP. And I have a slider down here that I could play, and it will

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:30.239
show how things have changed over time for these different countries, which creates a compelling

00:01:30.239 --> 00:01:37.599
story in its own way. But mostly I want to look at the app as it is. This app has a graph and a

00:01:37.599 --> 00:01:42.000
slider, and the two are connected in a way that you could play the graph across time using the

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:47.040
slider. And the app also has several different tabs. If we look at any of the tabs, they're just

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:51.519
sub-views of this data. So we get to look at countries on a continent by continent basis.

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:59.199
Except for Europe, I don't know what's going on there. We could, for any of these continents, we could play

00:02:00.559 --> 00:02:04.320
the animation and just see, you know, how things change for African countries, for example, or

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:09.039
American countries. And if you think about the way the app is designed, there's a lot of repetition

00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:15.039
here. Each tab, each view, does the same thing. It shows a graph, and the graph is connected to a slider.

00:02:15.039 --> 00:02:18.639
The only thing that's different between the different views is the actual dataset that

00:02:18.639 --> 00:02:22.960
appears in the graph. You know, if we come over here and look at the code for the app, we see that,

00:02:23.919 --> 00:02:26.720
you know, perhaps because of this, there's a lot of repetition in the code.

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:32.479
We do the same thing for each of the different tabs. On the server side, we have to recreate

00:02:32.479 --> 00:02:37.279
similar processes to make the graph and connect it to the slider. There's reactive values in there.

00:02:37.279 --> 00:02:43.119
And it ends up being a fairly long app, and it's a little hard to find any particular piece of code

00:02:43.119 --> 00:02:46.800
because there's so much code to wade through. And not only that, the code looks really similar to

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:50.240
other parts of the code, and it's kind of hard to be certain about where you're at in the app.

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:57.600
Now, I've taken the time to rewrite this app using Shiny modules. And when you use modules,

00:02:57.600 --> 00:03:02.000
the app looks like this. It's much more concise. It's much smaller. And what I've done is I've

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:07.520
what I've done is I've written an R script that takes the common pieces of code for each of the

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:13.360
tabs in our app and saves them to functions. So here I'm creating a function called gap module UI,

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:17.199
another function called gap module. Gap module does all the server side stuff to make that

00:03:17.839 --> 00:03:23.440
graph connect to the slider. And then in my modularized app, I load that R script. And

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:28.320
instead of calling, you know, there's where I want a slider. Here's where I want a graph. Here's how

00:03:28.320 --> 00:03:32.720
I want them to connect. I just call the functions that do that for me. So I'm calling gap module

00:03:32.720 --> 00:03:37.759
six times once for each view of the data. And then I'm calling, you know, the server side of

00:03:37.759 --> 00:03:43.039
gap module six times once for each view of the data. This app is much easier to understand. It's

00:03:43.039 --> 00:03:46.960
much easier to look at. And if I want to get into any of these individual pieces, then I could look

00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:53.039
at the definition of gap module UI or gap module over here. So this is the difference between a

00:03:53.039 --> 00:03:59.279
modularized app and an app that's not modularized. Once we took the time to write our modules,

00:03:59.279 --> 00:04:03.360
we can recall them as many times as we want. So I've called gap module six times here,

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:06.960
but I can also call it in a different app. So this is a great way to write some code that

00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:12.399
you can reuse later on. You find, for example, you're always creating some sort of upload API

00:04:12.399 --> 00:04:17.679
in your apps. You can create that API once and then call that module across all your apps and

00:04:17.679 --> 00:04:25.920
reuse it. So that's what modules are like conceptually. Here's our module in that last

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:33.440
app. Why would you use these modules? Well, you could see that it's very easy to reuse this code.

00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:37.359
Modules are sort of like functions. Once you take the time to write them, you could call them

00:04:37.359 --> 00:04:42.399
whenever you like to redo whatever that function does. In this case, what it does is create

00:04:42.399 --> 00:04:47.920
components of a shiny app. The next thing about modules are that they really isolate the

00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:52.880
functionality in your apps. Once you write your module function, all you have to think about

00:04:53.359 --> 00:04:57.519
is what that function does when you see it in your app. You don't have to think about

00:04:57.519 --> 00:04:59.440
how it does what it does.

